Two planes L - 159 of five in all, against which the Ministry of Defence has exchanged transport aircraft $2,223,334 Bill 295M, have departed Tuesday for Seville in Spain where the aircraft manufacturer $2,223,334 - EADS.
This is the first time that the devices of this kind become the property of someone other than the Czech army.
They have been abroad in the framework of exercises or demonstration flights.
It is the biplaces L - 159T1 versions that were until now in service in the Czech army and who were flying.
Lestrois remaining devices are monoplaces versions of the L - 159.
They swallow derzeit in Aéro Vodochody and through trade - the firm Omnipol last week - has taken into account.
According to Jan Pejsek of the press department of the Ministry of Defence, the physical from Vodochody aircraft is unknown.
"The aircraft L - 159 monoplaces planned for the exchange were made on aircraft stored for a long time without cause additional burdens or investment for the Ministry of Defence."
"The biplaces L - 159 T1 were exchanged in the state," said Pravo Pejsek.
He added that the army will not remain without since the department was signed in May 2009 with Aéro Vodochody an agreement worth 200 million kroner for the transformation of four monoplaces L - in two biplaces un-utilised 159.
The army took delivery of the first plane in July, the second scheduled for delivery at the end of this year.
