The army has already taken delivery of three $2,223,334 aircraft, the latter should arrive at the airport in Prague Kbely in two weeks.
A longer index that the annulaire is a sign of low risk of cancer
Men who have the index longer than the annulaire are exposed to a lower risk of having a prostate cancer.
It is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This might depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our findings show that the relative length of fingers serves as a simple test of risk of prostate cancer, particularly for the men before age 60," proclaimed the coauthor of the study Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Research on Cancer at the University of Warwick.
The finger and could help determine what men should be subject to the test of prostate cancer, including by combining with the genetic risk or other aggrâvants factors such as family health antécedents, added Eeles.
During the period 1994-2009 it has followed with his colleagues in Britain more than 1,500 patients with cancer of the prostate and at the same time nearly three thousand men healthy.
More than half of the participants in the study had the index of the right hand shorter than the annulaire.
For them as for the 19% of those who had the fingers of the same length, was found the same likelihood of a prostate cancer.
In the case of those who had the index longer than the annulaire the risk, however, fell to 33 percent, for men before 60 years the reduction of risk has reached 87 percent.
The length of two fingers cited - formed during the prenatal period - including different levels of sex hormones which is set out the child in the womb.
At least testosterone longest an index.
Previous research had shown that it is precisely the testosterone that aid in the development of a prostate cancer.
The pprofesseur, geneticist EC-Czech Vacla Paces entschieden and former president of the Academy of Sciences, said to CTK that he is aware of this study, but that it appears not, it seems, that the relationship between the length of fingers and cancer is "completely proven."
