Obama puts a brake on new oil drilling
There will be no new oil drilling in the Gulf of Mexico off the coast of Florida, southeast state of the United States, over the years to come.
The government in Washington gave an equivalent ban A ban and definitively cancelled its initial plans.
Even off the Atlantic coast, new drilling remain for the time being banned.
The Secretary of the Interior Ken Salazar made the announcement Wednesday.
It is the explosion in April, the drilling platform Deepwater Horizon " which is at the origin of this strict ban. This should remain in force at least for the next five years.
Faced with this accident that cost the lives of 11 employees and led to the greatest environmental disaster in the United States, President Barack Obama, under pressure from the opposition and the business sector, had indicated that he was willing to allow the completion of new drilling in the eastern part of the Gulf of Mexico.
Proponents of this solution and want to reduce the US dependence on foreign countries for the supply of oil.
The question of who bears the responsibility of the oil slick devastating in golf is not, to this day, finally resolved.
The British oil group, which is facing demands for compensation of several billion, is at the centre of the charges.
A committee of inquiry set up by Obama must present its findings current December.
In October, the Secretary of the Interior Ken Salazar had lifted the drilling freeze after the explosion of the platform.
As a result of this decision, various oil groups immediately submitted requests for new drilling projects.
With more stringent measures to control and stricter security procedures, Obama and Salazar want to prevent a new disaster.
The competent supervisory authority, which was discredited after numerous charges of corruption, is currently the subject of reforms in depth.
At the same time, Mr. Obama announced would remove the lucrative tax breaks for oil and gas groups.
The actors in this sector of activity now publicly warned against the fact that the flow of food in the Gulf would be much lower than is the case until now.
"The government's goal is to put a brake on the rapid growth of the oil and gas sector," according to the result of a current survey in the sector by the auditing firm BDO, before the drilling ban Wednesday.
Indeed, the American Enery Alliance regrets uncertainty this sector: "Nobody knows exactly that will change with the regulation."
The investments made in new support projects have been deferred until further order, at the expense of growth.
