On the shore of the river Bodo Jetty, Esther Badom says, once, she collected whole buckets of shrimp here.
But in the meantime the calm waters have completely dried up.
It was five years ago, a huge amount of oil gushed from a pipeline exploded in the vast swamp.
The fishermen capita the small town of Bodo must now pull for six hours to reach fish-bearing waters: the Ogoni country located in the heart of the Niger Delta is regarded as one of the world's most polluted regions.
The extent of the devastation is glaringly obvious leafing through the marshes of mangrove bisected by waters.
Instead of a clear water, the motorboating breaks a cradingue brown. Anyone who plunges his hand cut off all covered with oil.
Mangrove emerging soil as of liquorice roots of small sticks. The isolated palm leave sadly hang their fins.
The clouds of birds are seeking in vain, as is usually meeting in wetlands: as soon as the outboard motor stops, an eerily silence on this Uncooperative ire once that looks like a gas station by the smell it freed up.
"What happens here, it is war against the environment," says Akpobari air Celestine sad: "Our life is characterised by a permanent danger for health."
The comparison of wars is made.
The region where the Ogoni is a battlefield under siege for dozens of years: there are more than 60 years, the first European explorers have entered here; the first resistance was organized in the 1980s by Ken Saro-Wiwa. It was later executed. in 1993, the group Shell has had to suspend its production activities in this region because they had become very dangerous for its employees.
Today, the return to the country Ogoni is prohibited in this society: while more than 2 million barrel of black gold are daily pumped through more than 5,000 wells and 7,000 kilometres of pipelines in the whole of the Delta, three times larger like Switzerland, the oil fields of Ogoni countries are untapped, because the situation is too unstable for the oil group.
Every few hundred metres stand in the water of the tréteaux steel as bizarre sculptures: is very affectionate "Christmas trees" the heads of drilling holes.
They have up to 50 years, most are consumed by corrosion until benchmark.
Akpobari believes that a drilling head of this nature breaks from time to time piece, because a constant flow of crude oil flows in the water.
According to expert estimates, more than two billion litres spilled on the ecosystem in 50 years: each year, the amount of oil equivalent to that which has passed into the sea during the accident in the super-pétrolier "Exxon Valdez" there are 21 years off Alaska, one of the greatest environmental disaster in the history of humanity.
Who should bear the responsibility of the persistent environmental pollution? The answer to this question has divided the player.
For the group Shell, pipeline sabotage and the siphonage are responsible for more than 90% of the pollution. The tree-hugging Universityeducated see explosions heads of perforated drilling and pipelines as the main causes.
In 2008, the American scientist Richard Steiner begrudged group Shell to focus less stringent safety standards in Nigeria than anywhere else in the world: only the rate of waterpipes IPL-V is "still much higher than alleures."
Some emerging forms of mangroves to a place that, seen from afar, looks like an abandoned workshop, full of work and installed at the free air: they are completely naked and covered work up to the neck.
A fire twinkling under one of the many tons that sometimes related to the pipe, sometimes scattered without reason on the site must be répérés: a small illegal refinery.
Heat the oil in the cask for several hours, explains Michael, the team leader.
Initially, gasoline enters a container through pipes, then, at the end of the conduct of drops of kerosene fall and is finally diesel.
It is that Michael and his four colleagues every day four barrels of diesel 300L: "This tells us 34,000 Naira," about 22 dollars.
Delta residents benefit from the chronic shortage of fuel in the world's largest producer of oil in black Africa.
Nigeria has only one refinery.
Illegal refiners can sell at a price cheaper than ridiculously low of barely 40 Euro cents per litre of diesel: because they acquire free their first.
It is offered by the "gatekeepers" who put the network of pipelines in holes across the country of the Ogoni. According to the experts, the country loses this way at least 16 million litres of crude oil in the whole of the Niger Delta.
Only a small part quite misdesignation of the first purified temporarily stored illegally: organized crime networks that are among its members of senior politicians and military, pick up the lion's share of tankers and dumping on the world market.
The militant Akpobari believes that the debate on the question of whether we should attribute the environmental disaster or rather the subversive activities to the public or the lax mode of production is purely academic.
"If the oil companies were not seen as intruders and if the foundations of the life of the fishermen were not so profoundly destroyed, there would be no sabotage, theft and illegal refineries."
But Between - time, the relations of the Ogoni especially to Shell so deteriorated that it was more that the withdrawal of the group. "Perhaps that the operators of other nationalities, such as the Chinese, will be better."
Then, Michael becomes nervous.
"It is high time that you déguerpissiez" announces the robust oil worker.
"The soldiers can appear at any time."
If the illegal refiners are surprised by the special units of the armed forces, they will certainly not the subject of an arrest, but the more they provide bribes.
Even the soldiers mostly originating in the north of the country intend to take as all Nigerians of the raw material.
"At any point of view, this scarf low trick brought our country well," regrets Akpori.
