Mysterious work of $361,668
The agency International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) has new indications about a nuclear program developed by Syria.
But this country refuses to take a position on this subject, still less to submit to the control of the agency.
On the night of 5 to 6 September 2007 towards midnight, at least four Israeli I fighter aircraft attacked a mysterious form cubique building on the Syrian territory.
It is on the shore of the euphrate, the largest city located near is located 30 kilometers: it is Dair - On.
His name appears in the documents of the IAEA, because it is a question of the reactor that Syria has built post-CCH with the help of North Korea in parallélépipède rock, hidden in a valley marked by the lack of electricity.
According to a briefing US intelligence services, the CIA, dating from late April 2008, the current reactor, known as the name of the nearby, el Kibar, would be fit to produce plutonium, which would make atomic weapons.
In contrast, this technique is valid since the 1950s.
The CIA has shown a video presentation involving satellite images blurred.
Through the computer-animation by computer, it indicated the likely location of each component of the reactor before the destruction of the plant that is a miniature copy of the North Korean model of the nuclear plant in Yongbyon.
In addition, she has presented photos showing the building located near, even within it.
It seems that the reactor was on the verge of being put into service, but it was not yet equipped with fuel rods.
Today, more than three years after Israel's bombing raid, there is barely more information at the time, and even with the time the mystery deepens increasingly.
Former US President George W. Bush recently revealed in his memoirs that before the attack, the CIA was sure that Syria had built a reactor to el Kibar, but had peu' signs the country was "an active nuclear weapons program."
Some intelligence officers in Europe prefer to be more cautious on this subject and speak only of a "alleged reactor," even if they see the presentation of the CIA as "plausible."
They lack tangible evidence, as well as to the IAEA.
Questioned about the way it ensures that it is dealing with a nuclear reactor, a senior diplomat UN gave a terse response was that the IAEA had available "documents sufficient to ask questions."
The Syrian have abducted precipitately "unused military building" the rubble and proceeded to an orderly resolution of the ground.
However, in June 2008, a team of IAEA experts led by the former Chief Inspector Heinonen Oli, discovered el Kibar traces of uranium produced by men.
In addition, the IAEA received through a Member State of commercial providers of satellite images showing the moment which followed directly attack. It appears that the latter are louder than those presented by the CIA.
However, these photos are not available on the market because the sponsor anonymous, perhaps Israel, has acquired exclusive.
It is impossible for the IAEA to establish their authenticity objectively.
Syria has always ensured that she had never made a secret atomic program and that it had not built reactor.
Damascus maintains that the uranium found on the site comes from weapons used by Israel.
But the IAEA has rejected this argument after analyzing particles as implausible.
Since that time, damas refuses any discussion on this subject, as on satellite images.
In addition, Syria does not allow controllers to conduct a second inspection on the site of el Kibar and denied access to the rubble of buildings destroyed by the bomb.
But even Israel retains a stubborn silence.
Confirming the official position, Ehud Olmert, then Prime Minister in exercise at the time of the attack, recently said: "We shall never comments on this subject."
Thus the investigation of this case spotlight since June 2008 without that we reach a result and that it "increasingly turning into a serious problem of credibility of the Agency," as the high-ranking service recognizes a Western diplomat at the IAEA headquarters in Vienna, eventually it is a serious violation of the treaty to ban nuclear weapons.
The IAEA considers that to make progress, we need to clarify the existence of three other facilities that must have "a functional report" with the alleged reactor.
Until now, the inspectors have not indicated what facilities here, or what is their function or what we suspect to contain.
According to information published by the newspaper Süddeutsche Zeitung ', they are known within the IAEA respectively under the names of Marj - Sultan, Masyaf and Iskandariayah also the name of the neighbouring cities.
The Institute independent Institute for Science and International Security (International Institute for Science and International Security) Washington has identified these locations and found on satellite images a complex near Masyaf that would be very probably one of the suspects objects.
It is possible that he is in a military base or directly beside it; it is exactly the reason why Syria refuses access of the three sites to the inspectors of the IAEA.
In Vienna, it states that the Syrians fear that the inspection group is in fact spies who would be sent on behalf of the United States by the IAEA in order to spy on military installations.
Indeed, it is an information provided by the US secret agents who attracted the attention of nuclear inspectors.
The IAEA has information, including satellite photos, indicating that vehicles have been commuting between the three sites and the stone parallélépipède to transport substances.
A senior Western diplomat said in Vienna that at least one of the facilities could be used in the production of fuel."
It "would not indications regarding sensitive activities," such as enrichment and reprocessing of uranium, processes that are essential to the production of atomic weapons.
This type of reactor is certainly working through not enriched uranium.
Nevertheless, there is rigour plausible assumptions regarding the following basic questions: where should have come uranium and could later separated plutonium needed to manufacture of the bomb.
It is unknown if the rubble, which could hide traces of great value, were stored in the three sites.
When the hundreds of trucks loaded land will have disappeared, nobody will have information on the place of storage rubble.
For the IAEA, it is unlikely that Syria has been examined in 1998 the salt mine of al-Nedawat, Tibni, located only a few kilometres of el Kibar, on the other side of the Euphrates, to see if it can agree to the storage of radioactive waste.
In analysing recent photos taken by satellite for the account of the famous magazine Jane's Intelligence Review, the former inspector of the IAEA, Mr. Robert Kelley has established a link between them and the reactor in question.
Photos taken by satellite show that Syria has undertaken work of $361,668 in the three sites socially-disruptive and misplaced. huge containers when the IAEA began to demand access to these places.
It is possible that this is a coincidence, but it has not helped under-shooting suspicions.
It is said in diplomatic circles that the IAEA has spent several months to develop a plan for the inspections to make. This plan should allow Syria to preserve possible military secrets. only the time invested shows what interest the inspectors relate to this case.
Meanwhile, Damascus has also ignored the proposal.
There was a year ago, if Western diplomats in Vienna had not reported the destruction of the reactor, the emergency would not be reported for this case, says, for example, Glyn Davies, the US ambassador who men-tioned for a few months what is known as the special inspections, one of the most powerful means that the International Atomic Energy Agency has to implement its controls.
The Director of the IAEA, Mr. Yukiya Amano, who had to propose these inspections, has already spoken of "an option to which I am open to the future," but it is still reluctant.
This method involves a huge risk: firstly, it requires a majority in the Council of Governors of the IAEA and a good number of the 35 countries that are represented have no desire to see the situation escalate.
On the other hand, as the diplomat who gives réflechir: "At this point, if at the end they do not find anything"
