The democratic routine
Support for democracy in Latin America continues to increase, as the private company.
The crime has become a greater concern that unemployment.
And Brazil is seen as more influential than the United States in a large part of the region.
These are some of the conclusions of the latest survey Latinobarómetro taken in 18 countries and published in exclusivity by The Economist.
Given that the survey was conducted regularly since 1995, it follows the changes of attitude in the region.
Two elements stand out the results of the survey of this year, carried out in September and early October.
The first is the sunny enough mood of Latin America.
The second is the growing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its key institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries on the Pacific rim of South America (see Table 1).
For example in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy rose from a minimum of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It has also increased in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after having suffered a sharp drop in production last year.
But only about half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the region, are convinced democrats, which lowers the regional average (see Table 2).
Some 44% of respondents from the region were satisfied with the way democracy in their countries worked in practice; it is the same figure as last year but with a sharp increase on the 25% in 2001 (Chart 3)
Some 34% said that they had confidence in the parliament of their country and 45% in their government, the same as last year in both cases, but in sharp increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24% respectively).
It was ten years ago, the economic problems in Latin America have undermined support for democracy.
If it has held good during the financial crisis worldwide, it is certainly due to the fact that many American countries have not suffered only a brief recession and benefited from a strong recovery.
In addition, a social security network has contributed to protect the poor.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America has reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty rose only slightly in 2009 and has again fallen this year, to 32%).
But the mood varies considerably from one country to another (see Chart 4).
The good economic performance of Brazil and the popularity of its outgoing President Luiz Inàcio Lula da Silva, translates into a widely shared sense of progress
What is more rare in Mexico and Central America, where the recession has been more severe and where violent crimes have worsened.
It is only for the second time since the survey began that more respondents across Latin America as a whole have cited the crime rather than unemployment as the most important issue for their country (see Table 5).
About 31 percent say they or a loved have been victim of a crime during the past year; however, this figure is down from 38% last year and is the lowest since 1995.
A more robust economic performance is reflected in the increase of support for private enterprise and the market economy: approximately 71% of respondents from the region say that private enterprise is indispensable for the development, against 56% in 2007 (see Chart 6).
Some 58 percent believe that the market economy is the only system that will make their developed countries, against 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela are of this opinion (and 80% support the private company); even if their president left, Hugo Chávez, expropriating many private companies.
Brazil is the largest leader in the region, mentioned by 19% of respondents (from 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged compared to last year) and Venezuela (9%, down 11% since last year)
But the United States are considered the most influential country by respondents in Mexico and in most of Central America, while Venezuela enjoys this distinction in Ecuador, in the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
A vote tainted
No one expected to have the perfect general elections in Haiti on 28 November.
But it was far worse than the "outsiders" who wanted to help the country devastated and plunged in fear.
It has presented polling boxes and a new ballot, the ballot papers scattered in the goutières, voting offices ransacked and intimidation
Polling stations opened late in the evening.
Many Hatïens, including many who have been displaced following the earthquake in January, instead roamed in the neighbourhood to find where to vote.
Some of them eventually abandon.
A dozen candidates for the presidential, including several suspected favourites, have denounced the fraud and called for the annulment of the election.
Protests, sometimes violent, have exploded across the country.
Nevertheless, Edmond Mulet, the top official in Haiti to the United Nations, sees the event as "an election in many respects quite good."
Observers of the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community have cautiously "that they did not believe these irregularities, serious they are, had necessarily invalidated the process."
In other words, the show continues.
The electoral authority, the opponents are indebted to René Préval, President unpopular, and its candidate, Jude " Célestin, must announce the preliminary results on 7 December.
The second round expected is scheduled for January.
Any hope in the election is not lost.
The two opposition candidates, Michel Martelly, a rap musician, and Mirlande Manigat, a former first lady, withdrew from their initial appeal that the vote be declared null.
But there may be problems if Mr." Célestin, who has little or no noticeable support among the voters, is declared by the electoral authority as having reached the second toura reached the second round.
With a cholera epidemic raging, and more than 1 million earthquake survivors who are still living in tents, it was feared that participation would be.
In the case, many Haitïens wanted to vote but were prevented from doing so because of the disruption.
Nearly 250,000 cédula, needed to vote, were not yet distributed little time before the election.
The issue is important.
Donors see the election of a legitimate and popular government as an important step in the reconstruction of Haiti.
And, it is clear, Haitians do themselves.
The tippy feet to the centre
The weeks after being suddenly widow, Cristina Fernàndez, President of Argentina, has benefited from a wave of public sympathy that has improved its approval rate of 20 points, more than 50%; it is its highest level since it was elected in 2007.
Yet, turn this into a successful campaign for a second term at an election next year could depend on the choice of Mrs Fernàndez, visibly in mourning, according to which it would give up or not the intransigence of her late husband, predecessor and former political partner, Néstor Kirchner.
And, in this regard, the signs are still confused.
Mr. Kirchner, who has continued to manage the economic policy, even after his wife succeeded him as president, was used to develop budgets that underestimated tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
This has allowed the first couple to spend the additional income at will.
The government of Mrs Fernàndez has lost its majority in Congress last year, on paper.
But the opposition is divided, and the situation has fallen into disarray following the death of Mr. Kirchner of a heart attack on 27 October.
Some dissident members of the Malvinas movement to power rallied to Ms. Fernàndez.
But after chaotic sessions (where a parliamentary struck in the face one of his peers and where others have accused the government of corruption), the Congress failed to approve the 2011 budget.
"I am not going to compete," said the president.
Currently, the 2010 budget will be applied the next year, leaving the president even greater flexibility to spend at will.
The economy overheating widely: it is likely to grow by almost 9 per cent this year.
The official inflation rate is now at 11.1%, but many private estimates and wage demands of the unions, see this figure close to 30%.
Mr. Kirchner, who took office in 2003 when Argentina feared an economic collapse, has made a priority of the growth and the reduction of poverty, rather than the control of inflation.
He refused to deal with the IMF, it has harassed the private sector and served the INDEC, the statistical office, which was conducted in the falsification of statistics on the official inflation.
Ms. Fernàndez can now moderate these policies?
It has called for talks between private companies and union leaders.
And its officials say they want to limit wage increases next year to 18%.
The economy has been fueled by high world prices for agricultural exports from Argentina.
But inflation has eroded the boosting growth following a sharp devaluation in 2002.
It is perhaps the reason why Mrs Fernàndez shows signs of wanting to restore financial relations of Argentina to the rest of the world.
This year, the government has concluded an agreement with bondholders who had rejected an earlier restructuring forced debt that Argentina had not settled its deadlines in 2001.
Now Ms. Fernàndez seems to be edging towards year agreement with creditor government grouped in the Paris Club, to which it owes some $6. 7 trillion.
The Kirchners have always insisted on the fact that this could involve a surveillance by the IMF, as is customary.
But the last month, Amado Boudou, the Minister of Economy, announced that the fund would provide a "technical assistance" to design a new national index of consumer prices; what looks like a prelude to the remediation of the INDEC.
It is not clear whether Ms. Fernàndez wants to stay in politics beyond the end of his mandate, now that her husband is no longer on its side.
If it does so, it needs to win the support of the middle class, among which the kirchnerisme is very resolutions8.
When the Argentinians will be returned from their summer holidays in March, the wave of sympathy for it will be dropped.
If it wants to win another election, it will have to decide whether or not to repudiate, without noise, many policies of her husband.
