A microbe tolerant arsenic raises the possibility of new types of life on Earth, or elsewhere.
The discovery of a strange bacteria, which can use arsenic as one of its nutrients, broadens the scope to find new forms of life on Earth and perhaps beyond.
Although researchers have discovered the bacteria unusual here on Earth, they say that this shows that life has opportunities beyond the major elements that were considered essential.
"This organization has a dual capacity."
"It can be developed with phosphorus, arsenic."
"This is why it is very special, even if it is far from being a form of life really" foreign ," said Paul Davies C. W. of the State University of Arizona, coauthor of the report in Thursday's online edition of the journal Science.
Six major elements have long been seen as essential to life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorous and sulfur.
But researchers have discovered that the bacteria, discovered in Lake Mono, California, is able to continue to develop after having replaced phosphorus by arsenic.
"One wonders what is still possible," said Ariel Anbar D. of Arizona State University, coauthor of the report.
The discovery is important in research of life beyond the Earth because researchers must be able to recognize the life, what what life, said Anbar.
The study focuses on a microbe found on Earth.
However, the announcement of a press conference to discuss the details of the discovery, has generated, which has not disclosed widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could disclose the discovery of extra-terrestrial life.
This has not been the case.
The discovery "shows that, in other global environments, organizations may be able to use other elements for 26/97 biochemistry and that the whole" standard "elements, that we consider absolutely necessary for life, could not be fixed," said Charles Cockell, a professor at the Institute for Scientific Research decrease998-1003 and spacial, Open University, Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
"This work is new because it shows the substitution of a fundamental to another in biochemistry and biochemical structure," said Cockell.
This was not a fortuitous discovery.
Felisa Wolfe - Simon of the Institute of Astrologie of NASA, who led the study, has chosen the lake Mono because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, she speculated that a microbe exposed to the two substances may be able to replace one another.
"Arsenic is poisonous mainly because its chemical behaviour really is similar to that of phosphorus."
"As a result, the organizations have trouble distinguishing these components separately."
"But arsenic is sufficiently different that it does not exactly as the phosphorus-based; he got inside and, in some way, the work of our biochemical machine," said Anbar.
Researchers collected the bacterium known under the name of GFAJ -1 and exposed to increasing concentrations of arsenic which she was able to adapt and grow.
The microbe grows better with the phosphorus-based, but the fact that it can live with arsenic raises the possibility that a form of life using arsenic can occur naturally, or elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or the moon where arsenic is more frequent.
Jamie S. Foster, assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said that the idea, according to which the arsenic could be replaced by the phosphorus-based, was not new, but nothing has ever shown that this could walk.
Arsenic was more frequent at the beginning of the existence of the Earth, she said; thus, the researchers have hypothesized that the first forms of life could have used.
This suggests that there may be other ways to train the life, not just the way life on Earth was formed at the beginning," said Foster, who was not part of the research team from Wolfe - Simon.
The research was funded by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institute of Health.
