Senator Ensign inculperont not prosecutors
Prosecutors of the Department of Justice have lifted the criminal charges on Senator John Ensign, stemming from a case linked to an assistant of a former campaign and its efforts to obtain lobbying work for the husband of the woman, announced Wednesday of Senator lawyers.
The decision ended the most serious legal threat faced by Mr. Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was seen as a possible candidate Republican in the presidential election in 2012 until the scandal surrounding his case is the big national titles last year and undermine his career.
The office of Mr. Ensign said he was "very pleased" by the decision, result of a year-long investigation.
The senator could still be exposed to disciplinary measures taken by the Senate Committee on Ethics.
Counsel for Mr. Ensign said that the Department of Justice had "informed that Senator Ensign was no longer the subject of the inquiry and that he did not intend to maintain some kind of accusation against him in this case."
The Department of Justice has declined to comment on this subject.
The announcement came as a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Department of Justice, according to which there is significant evidence that Mr. Ensign would have conspired to violate a criminal prohibition federal lobbying.
Interviews, e-mails and other documents, first disclosed in October 2009 in the New York Times, indicated that Mr. Ensign helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, to obtain a lucrative lobbying work to win the silence of Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the case of Senator with it.
Ms. Hampton once served as Treasurer in a campaign to Ensign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political funding to find work for Mr. Hampton and, secondly, he defended their rights after they have committed Mr. Hampton to lobby for them, according to documents and interviews.
Given that Mr. Hampton had recently been a collaborator of Mr. Ensign, he was banned for a year by the law to lobby his former employer or the Senate in its entirety.
The ethics experts have argued that the unusual agreement between Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were friends before the case, seems in conflict with the so-called ban of the revolving door of lobbying.
According to the evidence that has been made public, "there is a prima facie case of a conspiracy to violate and substantial violations of the law of the revolving door," said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in the defence of clients of an investigation by the government.
Although the judge of the department has refused to explain the reasoning behind the decision in the case Ensign, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers have said that the department seemed to be wary of political prosecutions after a certain number of high-level cashed setback by his section of the public integrity, including the decision last year to abandon the prosecution against former Senator Ted Stevens accused of lack of prosecution.
Federal prosecutors have clearly afraid to take the weapons, said Melanie Sloan, executive director of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, an advocacy group that has received several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"This basically says high ranking government officials can now assumes the laws don't apply to them," she added.
Paul Coggins, Mr. Ensign main lawyer, said in an interview that he had received Monday a telephone call from a prosecutor from the Department of Justice and followed the next day, saying that the department was not seeking charges against his client.
The team of lawyers to Mr. Ensign had cooperated with the prosecutors to try to persuade them that the senator, as his office reaffirmed Wednesday in a news release, "had acted in accordance with the law."
Mr. Coggins refused to clarify the legal arguments that he had made to the public prosecutor's office.
"I am not comfortable going into the details of my discussions with the Department of Justice, except to say that we believe that they have made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Elections Commission has decided to abandon an investigation following a complaint independent by the ethics group, arguing that the payment of 96.000 per the parents of Mr. Ensign Hampton violated the federal election law.
The electoral commission has said that it was not enough evidence to prove that the money was everything except a gift.
NV Energy, an important Nevada company that has long supported the senator, is a company for which Mr. Ensign helped Mr. Hampton to find lobbying work.
An Email sent in December 2008 showed that, after the company has welcomed Mr. Hampton as a lobbyist, the Chief of Staff to Mr. Ensign, John Lopez, contacted Mr. Hampton and told him that he "martelait" the Department of the Interior on an issue in dispute.
Mr. Ensign has also participated in a lunch with Mr. Hampton and another customer Nevada, Allegiant Air, and it has asked the Secretary of Transportation to set a meeting on behalf of the airline after having committed Mr. Hampton to lobby.
When the news of the case have surfaced last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned from his position as leader in the fourth Republican in the Senate.
After having maintained a low profile for several months, Mr. Ensign said two weeks ago that he had the intention to seek a third term in the Senate.
In announcing that Mr. Ensign was the target of a criminal investigation, his spokesman, Jennifer Cooper, said that the senator hoped the Ethics Committee quickly follow the example of the Department of Justice and would end its investigation.
Senator Ensign looks forward to continuing his hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada, she said.
The appeal of Cheshire will expose to Twitter
Half a dozen of them were in the process of typing away in the rows of the courtroom.
They were consigning all minutes of testimony horrific reports via Twitter.
At the end, the defense said that there were more than 140,000 messages on the trial of the case of rape and children attached to their bed in a house that was burned down.
On Thursday, the trial largely followed Steven J. Hayes, who was convicted of the murder of three members of the family Cheshire, in Connecticut, should lead to a formal end where the judge would impose the death penalty, passed by the board.
But lawyers for Mr. Hayes have already submit evidence to the court outlining appeal arguments, likely to occupy the courts for years.
This is provocative, it is that the intense stories on the trial - as well as the widespread use and extended by journalists of Twitter - have created an "atmosphere of circus," if widespread and instant EMTNS with incendiary details that the board has been badly affected by the passions of the public.
The request could push the appellate judges to debate on the question of whether the new technologies require new rules in the courtroom.
"I have experience at this trial and I think that there is a real danger, the introduction of new technologies in the courtroom violates the rights of the person to a fair trial," said Thomas J. Ullmann, lawyer for Mr. Hayes, chief lawyer.
The trial judge, Jon C. Blue of State Superior Court, laconiquement rejected the claims last week in the judgment, saying that the media were "carefully controlled" and that there was no evidence that the board would have been animated by the passion.
But this does not seem to be the last word on the issue.
The appeal courts have recognized for decades that the media coverage of WellKnown case may raise questions about the fairness of a trial.
In a judgment of 1966 landmark, the Supreme Court of the United States quashed the conviction of a Cleveland osteopaths, Dr. Sam Sheppard, for the murder of his wife, supporting in its decision that there was an "atmosphere of carnival at trial" because of the media.
The crime is considered by some to have been the inspiration for the television and the film "the fugitive's."
Some lawyers have said that the appeal courts to review half a century later the conviction of Mr. Hayes may be curious given the argument that new rules could be required to manage the means of communication courtrooms, unimaginable at the time of the case of Dr. Sheppard.
"There is a general reason to worry about the impact of new media" in the large-scale trial, said John J. Donohue III, a professor at the Stanford Law School who has studied the death penalty in Connecticut and has written a report according to which it was arbitrarily applied.
Professor Donohue said that some judges of appeal could be intrigued by the idea that the limitation of instant communication from courtrooms could allow for fairer trial.
The case of Twitter is one of many described by counsel for Mr. Hayes, likely to be discussed for years, which delays the execution.
The defence lawyers claim, for example, that Mr. Hayes would have suffered damage when the judge refused to allow them to test the reactions of potential jurors showing grisly photos of criminal scenes at the selection of the jury.
Some of the jurors said they had been horrified by the pictures of the victims, Jennifer Hawke - Petit, 48 years old, and his daughters, Hayley, 17, and Michaela, 11 years.
The defence lawyers say they will also challenge the constitutionality of the death penalty and that they will argue that the judge was unjustly expelled one juror, who had been critical to the prosecutors, and that he improperly put pressure for a verdict in taking the unusual decision to bring the board to deliberate in a weekend.
The jurors were not sequestered.
But their arguments on the effect of the intense media coverage of the trial could be the greatest source of interest.
They noted in a challenge against the verdict, filed last month, that the case dominated the media scene in Connecticut and that it was discussed during the election campaign by candidates for the post of governor and the Senate of the United States.
They have maintained that the computer media to fan the flames of the emotion of the case.
"The daily tweets scuffle media, cameras and journalists to the thecourthouse," wrote the lawyers, "looked like nothing of what was seen here, in New Haven, and perhaps even at the national level."
Their focus on the cover of the Twitter system is controversial.
In the interviews, some journalists have said that the statement, according to which the new instant were more inflammatory challenge releases more slowly, was a luddiste that would impoverish the Court's policy governing media coverage of future trial.
But some lawyers have said that the appeal courts étaitent often attracted by the arguments that the technological and social change requires adaptation by the courts.
Counsel for Mr. Hayes insist on this claim.
In their case, they are a reference to the decision of the Supreme Court of 1966, which had overturned the conviction of Dr. Sheppard due to media coverage of the trial and they indicated that they invoqueraient the need for new rules for the new media.
"This affair," wrote they ," represents Sheppard v.. Maxwell of the 21st century."
Civility can bring the divisions?
After a campaign marked by invective and the negativity, a minimum of civility erupted in Washington this week.
Is it a harbinger of a genuine bipartisan cooperation forward or an illusory time before the rapid return to the partisan struggle in the capital?
The meeting Tuesday between President Obama and the leaders of Congress has produced no breakthrough on the key issues that must be dealt with during the "lame duck" session.
But obviously, there are at least had a polite discussion on the differences of the two parties as well as on the recognition of their shared responsibility to govern, rather than another episode where each side wanted to score points. Contentless rating supporter.
The public meeting on Wednesday of the Committee on the deficit has been equally civilized president, despite the political differences that remain between members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created a mutual respect across the ideological divide, but which, however, still divides the members.
It is barely sufficient to say that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
The two parties are now in a period of trial and test for signs of cooperation and compromise mutual, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters for a renewed partisan war.
That is why the meeting on Tuesday and subsequent comments from participants have unveiled a minimum requirements or charges.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too large and too deep to suggest a rapid change in the climate that has existed over the past two years.
Whether taxation, spending, health care or the rights, the two parties remain miles of distance.
However, the election of November had moderate Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no doubt that things have changed the tone," said Pete Wehner, an official of the Bush administration, now on the side of the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
"It is inevitable after the elections.
The elections are causing partisan passions, and then they estomptent.
This is good."
On some issues, including those on the agenda of the "lame duck" session, the Republicans and Democrats have no other choice than to find a solution.
The Bush tax cuts will expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of it.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve a part or the whole, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise is conceivable on the extension of unemployment benefits, if only because the Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favour of tax cuts for the wealthy, while denying unemployment benefits for unemployed workers.
After the meeting Tuesday at the White House, more optimism hangs on a possible agreement on the questions raised during the session on the "lame duck," with the ratification of the pact "New START."
But official William Galston put it, of the Brookings Institution, warns that a successful cooperation on the most pressing problems of the "duck" session will lead not necessarily a better understanding between the two parties when the 112th Congress meets in January.
Instead of this, he said, a period of disagreement is likely, even inevitable.
"Once the things that need to be made will be, the psychology in the short term will be one of confrontation," he said.
Wehner also expressed scepticism widely shared that civility would lead to a genuine cooperation.
"I consider most of what happens between now and 2012 as a pre-show or a shadow - boxing compared to the main event of 2012, he said.
The reasons are closely related to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and the electors present at the tea that have contributed to its development.
However, Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know that they must try to be up to their promises to reduce public spending and to repeal the new law on health care.
These partisan positions are now clear in the first reactions to the recommendations of the Committee of the deficit that include reforming the tax code and to increase certain taxes, pushing back the retirement age and reduce spending.
The co-chairmen Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles chose one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and have, by themselves, imposed the issue of the deficit on the agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the committee, composed of 18 members, to issue their plan as a formal recommendation, and they have had difficulty in achieving this number.
The greatest resistance are still among the elected representatives of the group, which suggests that there is on tax issues, at least today, few grounds or willingness to compromise.
Galston provides two phases in the fighting between the White House and the Republicans in Congress.
The first will come the next year in the form of clashes supporters, given that the Republicans assail Obama in terms of budget, tax and health care; then be followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What is the cause of change?
Public opinion.
It is widely shown that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still wants to see the two parties work together.
If the confrontation leads to an impasse, as in 1995, when the two parties will attentively observe public reaction.
Those who will be judged in loss will have to change course and find compromises.
But this would be an optimistic point of view.
Partisanship and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid 1990s and there seems to be more ideological gap between Obama and the Republicans in Congress that there was then between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans.
At the same time, the activists of the two parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a larger election in 2012.
Given this reality, civility exposed this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on the part of both parties to find an accommodation on the issues that divide again.
American disclosed documents describe Moscow as a haven of corruption
The control of the city is between the hands of a "Kleptocratie" and put up to the Kremlin part of bribes and money that it collects, said the US Embassy in Russia in a note in February.
The police and the Federal Security Service realize huge racketeering that help explain the high cost of living in Moscow, he said that.
They collect the money not only legitimate businesses, but also of organized crime groups.
Each layer of bureaucracy - what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called the "vertical of power" - takes its share as the money passes to the top of the scale.
The note of service, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was mailed Wednesday by Wikileaks on its website.
The score is based on sources whose names have been cleared.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still mayor of Moscow; and it is largely responsible for corruption.
He was dismissed in October by President Dmitri Medvedev, but there has since been few traces of cleaning.
Luzhkov and his wife, Elena Batourina, who has a leading construction company, have always denied the accusations of corruption over the years; and it has won several defamation trial on these charges.
In September, he said that a Russian TV channel, when he was questioned about a documentary suggesting that he was corrupt: "It is crazy, it is to throw, it is anything."
The Russians believe, with an overwhelming majority, that their society is corrupt; according to the polls.
But it is unusual to find the information set out in a record of Embassy; and it is incredible to conceive that this would be diplomats from a foreign country to do so.
The direct link established between the government of the city of Moscow and crime has led some people to name the "dysfunctional" and to say that the government functioned more as a kleptocratie that a government ," according to the note to the embassy.
"The criminals enjoy a" krysha " (the term used in the world criminal/the mafia which means literally" roof " protection) that passes through the police, the Federal Security Service (FSB), the Ministry of the Interior (MVD) and the prosecutor's office, and throughout the bureaucracy of the government of the city of Moscow.
"The analysts to identify a three-level structure in the Moscow criminal world."
"Luzhkov is at the top."
"The FSB and the MVD and militias are at the second level."
"Finally, ordinary criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the lowest level."
"It is an inefficient system in which criminals fills a void in some areas where the city does not provide certain services."
The report indicates that the FSB breaststroke money larger companies and that the police ciblent small.
A source, he said that, "explained that business owners of Moscow understood that it was preferable to obtain the protection of the MVD and the FSB (rather than organized crime), because not only, they have more weapons, more resources and more power than the criminal groups, but they are also protected by law."
"This is the reason why the application for protection by the criminal gangs is not as high."
The memo noted that, although the collection of the money is extended, protection itself can be uneven; even those who pay are sometimes subject to an arrest.
Those who do not pay quickly see their business shut down under a pretext or another.
Medvedev has mentioned several times the fight against corruption but he admitted the little progress.
The note of the embassy sends reports showing men who bring suitcases, probably met money, up to the Kremlin.
"In its fight against corruption, Medvedev depends on the bureaucrats," said in a recent interview Gueorgui Satarov, director of the think tank Indem " of Moscow.
"But it is part of this bureaucracy."
"It is not part of a political class because it is not in Russia."
Without the policy, without opposition, without separation of powers, he said that corruption is inevitable.
According to the Indem, the costs of corruption, to the whole of Russia, to more than $300 billion per year.
The country has been ranked 154e in a recent survey on the overall perception of corruption by the non-governmental organization Transparency International (countries are ranked the least corrupt).
The disclosure of the note from the US Embassy, which was carried out yesterday, late in the evening, Moscow time, remuera with certainty of discontent within the Russian government, although Luzhkov can be faulted, to a certain extent, for the failures of Moscow, this could be an opportunity for the Kremlin to show that it is in the process of solving the problem.
Interviewed by the CNN Larry King, Putin has hypothesized that the WikiLeaks documents could be a manufacturing and has reacted with anger to the remarks that US diplomats had disclosed to the appellant Batman and bringing Medvedev Robin.
"The problem is based on the fact that it is our interaction, important domestic policy in this country, he said.
"But to be honest with you, we do not suspect that this would be achieved with such arrogance, such pressure and, you know, in opposition to ethics."
The veterans of the Khmer Rouge forced to confront the past
In a classroom poorly lit with decrepit decommissioned concrete walls of the secondary school of Anlong Veng non-quality, the Director has mentioned the man who had built, the last leader of the Khmer Rouge, Ta Mok.
"Everybody here likes Ta Mok."
"It was a good leader, and he was concerned about her people," said Sreng Kor Ma, 42-years-old.
Known as "the butcher" for his brutality, when he was at the head of the Khmer Rouge, the commander remains popular in this isolated bastion of former Khmer Rouge northwest of Cambodia where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure; and where thousands of former soldiers of the organization still live today.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge went to the government, the long-standing loyalty is finally challenged Anlong Veng.
In April, a local truth and reconciliation forum enabled the victims to respond publicly to the people who had participated in the scheme.
In June, the government has distributed a manual of high school, for the first time, teaches the history of the Khmer Rouge to the children of his former soldiers.
And, in July, a Cambodian court jointly run with the United Nations, made its first sentence for a former member of the Khmer Rouge, condemning, to 35 years in prison, the former head of the notorious Tuol Sleng torture centre, Kaing Khek Iev, better known under the name "Duch."
Before this evolution of the situation, the anxiety has increased with veterans of the Khmer Rouge Anlong Veng, complicating the efforts of reconciliation and their wishes to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
"There is resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rouge, but they are powerless to do anything," said Chhang Youk, director of the Documentation Centre of Cambodia, an independent organization that conducts research on the regime.
"For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious but the regime has become a symbol of evil."
"The situation generates divisions within families."
During the reign of the Khmer Rouge in Cambodia, from 1975 to 1979, approximately 1.7 million people were executed or died of starvation, disease or overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the government of Pol Pot in 1979, the rest of the regime and its army have fled to Cambodia's border with Thailand.
There, they have launched an insurgency that has lasted until the last movements go in December 1998.
While Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary heading guerrilla base located in the mountains of western Cambodia and in the jungle, Ta Mok was preparing a response to Anlong Veng.
But in the mid 1990s, after a peace agreement sponsored by the UN has led to the first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of combatants Khmer Rouge began defecting to the government, culminating with the capitulations Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998 and Ta Mok, who had head, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the mountains near Dangrek.
He died in a prison in Phnom Penh in 2006 pending trial.
Without their benefactors, most veterans Khmer Rouge have sunk in abject poverty, common to rural areas of Cambodia, and many remain nostalgic for the movement.
Although a few elite officers Khmer Rouge kept their positions of local leader in exchange for having tabled the weapons, it is not qualified farmers low rank and file.
"These people have benefited little follow-up after the surrender," said Sok Leang of the Centre for justice and reconciliation which organizes public forums throughout Cambodia, including Anlong Veng.
"They are saturated with the agrarian utopian ideology of the regime."
"They were reared in a context where business is a foreign concept."
Sor Lim, aged 55 years old, who has joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, has fought in the jungle around Anlong Veng before moving in 1998 as poor rice grower.
"Life under the Khmer Rouge was good," he said.
"Your Mok feeds everyone."
But now, life is difficult because we must meet our own needs."
The Khmer Rouge tribunal has also caused concerns here.
The court should, at the beginning of next year, begin the judgment of Nuon Chea president Khieu Samphan Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge Minister.
The mandate of the tribunal is to judge the senior leaders and the main responsibility for the crimes, but it has not said if he continued beyond these four cases.
It alonger to calm the fears of Anlong Veng.
Recent media speculation turned to Im Chaem, aged 64, former district chief in the province of Banteay Meanchey in the reign of the Khmer Rouge in the 1970s.
In 2007, she said researchers of the Documentation Centre of Cambodia that she had supervised the construction of the dam of Trapeang Thma, a project where thousands of workers forced would have found the death.
Recently, at a torrid evening, Im Chaem was returning from work in the field near his wooden house on stilts, on a dirt road outside of Anlong Veng.
While the sun cast long shadows on the grass parched, Im Chaem refused to discuss his past within the Khmer Rouge.
If the court, she said, she had refused to go.
"Cambodia is peaceful and stable," d'Addario said.
"If there are more prosecutions, there will be war."
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who has been defection of the Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also warned repeatedly that instability would happen if the court continued several suspects, although experts and historians dispute this.
"Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past, he said.
But confront the past is everything that Cambodia must do to move forward, said Youk Chhang, the documentation centre.
"The Khmer under reconciliation is to reconnect the broken pieces, he said.
"We must put these pieces together so that we can understand."
The centre has produced the first manual approved by the government on the Khmer Rouge, "a history of Democratic Kampuchea, composed of 75 pages."
It has distributed to Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to textbooks history of the Ministry of Education, designed for high schools, which contained fewer than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
As in most of Cambodia, the young Anlong Veng are only a few details on the Khmer Rouge, in spite of the city's links to the regime.
Touch Valeak, aged 19, student at the high school of Anlong Veng, said that the new manual helped students understand a significant part of their history.
But his parents have reacted skeptically when he returned with the book home to study.
"My family rejects many parts of the manual and the court," he said.
"They are suspicious because they do not know exactly how many people the court will continue."
Such resistance has made the complex and difficult process of reconciliation, said Sok Leang.
But the public forums, the manual and the court are beginning to have an impact, he said.
However, the Khmer Rouge retain a powerful atrait here.
In the heights of the mountains of Dangrek, a road, invaded by weeds and littered with plastic bags, led to a black soot rectangle, covered in a rusty tin roof.
The body of Pol Pot was burned here on a pile of tyres after his death in 1998.
Sothea Nuom, aged 31 years, mobile telephone saleswoman roadside, said she knew little about the man who has been cremated at this location.
"But it has a great spirit; and many people go to pray, she said.
It was the anniversary of Nuom Sothea and, later that day, she has planned to walk to the last place of rest of Pol Pot where it would leave a bouquet of ripe bananas in the hope of bringing luck.
Belarus agrees to give up its stock of weapons-grade uranium
The government of Belarus announced Wednesday that it would abandon its stock of highly enriched uranium, a key component for nuclear weapons; this decision is part of a surprise victory of the campaign of President Obama to secure the nuclear materials in the world
The agreement was disclosed in a news release spouse published after the Secretary of State Hillary Rodham Clinton met by the Minister of Foreign Affairs, Sergei Martynov, on the sidelines of a summit on security.
The US government had tried for years to convince the Belarus-EU to renounce the highly enriched uranium and seemed to have reached the horizon last spring.
But US officials have said in the Washington Post that some classified operations have been conducted with Belarus over the last two months to eliminate CDN$188 books of the weapons-grade uranium from a research centre of Belarus.
This has opened the way to an agreement Wednesday to eliminate the rest of the approximately 500 books, according to an official who spoke on the condition of anonymity because of the sensitivity of the issue.
The agreement seems to be one of the most important results of the Nuclear Security Summit of 47 nations, held at the initiative of Obama; where Belarus was excluded.
Apparently, it has been profitable VEEP invitation to the former Soviet republic in the wake of the summit, in 2012.
"I am really fascinated by the fact that they want a seat at the Summit of 2012 Nuclear Security Summit of security."
"This proves that this process works," said Ken Luongo, president of the Partnership for global security, a group of promotion of nuclear safety.
Clinton called the agreement "very significant, important" conducted by Belarus.
Obama has pledged to Prague in April 2009 to secure all nuclear materials vulnerable across the world in the coming four years.
Since then, the US government has helped six countries to get rid of all their highly enriched uranium.
Belarus would be the seventh.
A dozen countries have done under the administration of George W. Bush.
At the time of the summit on Obama's nuclear security, the Belarussian President Alexander Lukashenko, has said that the nation will never renounce its uranium.
"We kept of highly enriched uranium, hundreds of kilograms of what is essentially the weapons-grade uranium and the low-enriched uranium," said Mr. Lukashenko.
"It is our product... we will not produce dirty bombs, and we will not sell to anyone."
"We will use it for research purposes, that's all."
Belarus is closer to the United States a few months; however, Préspa of interest to reach an agreement.
The first implementation to remove uranium from Belarus, in October, has been particularly complicated because the material was slightly irradiated, said officials.
He has been charged on a special train has travelled more than 1,300 miles up to a facility in Russia to be stored and eliminated, said officials.
The second operation was completed Monday and was carried out by air, according to the officials.
The US government has spent $13 million in its efforts, in large part to replace the research facilities of Belarus with low-enriched uranium; unsuitable for weapons.
"A careful coordination and organisation have been implemented in order to strengthen the trust," leading to the agreement signed by President Clinton, said Andrew Bieniawski, head of the Department of Energy specializing in the Menace world.
According to the estimates of the James Martin Center of Nonprolifération Study, Belarus had this year at least 88 pounds of weapons-grade uranium, as well as hundreds of kilograms of highly enriched uranium.
Belarus seeks to eliminate its stockpiles by 2012, according to a joint statement.
Relations between Belarus and the United States were strained for years, mainly due to the harsh repression by Lukashenko of Human Rights.
But the statement Wednesday suggested a potential revival.
"While welcoming the progress on these issues of global security, the United States and Belarus have recognized that an increased respect for democracy and human rights in Belarus remained essential to improving bilateral relations; and the development of the country and its citizens," she said.
