Red Bull triumph in F1 with a secret weapon of Siemens
Software creates improvements on cars in real time.
As soon as Red Bull treet entered the world of Formula 1 in 2004, its history in this sélecte universe of speed has been marked by the surprise and success.
In a first time, nobody has taken into account the options for a new stable who had just arrived, despite the upward trajectory of recent seasons, the past November, in the final phase of the championship they have all backed the triumph of Ferrari of Fernando Alonso.
Without Arlije skill as a pilot of the champion, the German of goaltender Sebastian Vette, the capacity of the Renault engine which drives his car in the world of Formula 1 we talk about the legend of the "secret weapon" that the multinational company Siemens put the hands of Red Bull for Tran­sformin­g in a team winner.
It is actually a powerful software simulation process that the German company has launched on the market in 2007 with objectives very far away from the high automobilistique competition.
Appointed, this powerful computer instrument was used to create the fabricantes assembly chains throughout the world, power stations, the instruments of high precision.
The goal is COUNCIL., accurately simulate the product or process prior to build a real way, avoiding -Defects and avoidable costs.
Has facilitated the development of Canon cameras, Sukhoi aircraft or most famous vehicles from Nissan.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of the industrial division of Siemens, explains the fact that the use of this instrument computer in its plant in Formula1 led Red Bull to create and execute "in few hours, almost in real time," the amendments, changes and improvements detected during races and tests.
Russwurm explained that the stables of the year 1992 had an average of 10 technicians in their teams who was able to introduce a maximum of three or four improvements on the vehicles each season.
In the Red Bull team work today 180 young professionals of high qualifications, equipped with powerful computers analyze and plan any changes to the cars.
The leader of Siemens explained that the software is able to analyse and improve all elements of the cars of Red Bull except for the engine, which is responsibility of Renault.
It amends the materials, fuel, aerodynamics and security features.
The changes may move from the virtual reality simulator to reality in less than 24 hours, thanks to advanced systems of production by laser and high-tech autoclaves.
As a single limitation of this madness of technology development there is the amount of $40 million that each team of Formula1 can spend as limit each season to facilitate competition.
Red Bull has ADFSI high-tech plant to create and produce its cars in a locality to 50 kilometres of London.
These are two buildings where the visits, especially for journalists, are restricted.
Everything that happens there is considered "top secret."
The staff for this duty 580 people, presented herein two pilots, the champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
The hero of the Formula1 of Red Bull, no doubt, is the recent champion Sebastian Vetell.
Between the huge technological resources that the mark of energy drinks has places in the service of its participation in the channels-a, there are other hidden protagonists, whose activity is invaluable and zero visibility.
