The Pakistani nuclear program generates a great concern to the United States
Islamabad product of atomic weapons to "a faster pace than any other country."
The filtrations of Wikileaks confirms the connection between the Taliban and Pakistan.
The contents of the correspondence between the US embassy in Pakistan and the Department of State of United States filtered through the portal Wikileaks confirms the enormous concerns about Pakistan's nuclear program in Washington.
The details illuminating and flavorful that offer on the content of the conversations and thoughts of diplomatic representatives North American accredited in Islamabad, the documents reveal the fact that the cooperation between the two countries in the field of nuclear safety, instead of increasing, "declined" and that the unstable Asiatic country produces nuclear weapons "at a faster pace than any other country in the world."
The peculiarity of the Pakistani nuclear program - the fact that the weapons are not assemblies, but they are emmagasinnées by components to make it difficult destruction in case of attack - is one of the main reasons for concern in Washington.
Thus, the ambassador to Pakistan, Anne W. Patterson, lists in a report before the visit of the former National Security Advisor James Jones: "The close proximity of certain nuclear facilities in the territory under Taliban attack, the dispersal of nuclear materials that the rumour and the vulnerability of the transportation of nuclear materials."
The large number of people involved in the nuclear arsenals and missile programs are considered, not only by the United States, but also by Russia, such as proliférant and a reason to maintain custody.
"Pakistan has staff with strict religious beliefs to protect the nuclear facilities; given the decline of cultural and educational levels, the extremist organisations have more opportunities to recruit people who worked in the nuclear or missile programs," said the expert Yuri Korolev, the Department of Russian Externes during a meeting with its American counterparts.
The new documentation filtered through the portal of Julian Assange is cooperation increasingly reduced between the United States and Pakistan in the field of nuclear proliferation and the high level Pakistani production of nuclear armas.
A dispatch from the Embassy in May, which has characterized as "frustrating" communication with Pakistan, supports the following: "Transparency is frequently non-existent; the offers of help remain unanswered or are eliminated."
In another message, Peter Lavoy, an official of the National Intelligence for the Southern Asia, noted that "despite the economic catastrophe, Pakistan produces nuclear weapons at a faster pace than any other country in the world."
Ambassador Patterson also request to Washington, during a visit by the head of the army, General Ashfaq Kayani, whether understand "very clearly" in charge that "the Army of Pakistan must finish with the tacit support for terrorist groups."
