Obama promotes Twitter legislation for undocumented students
"If you agree with the approval of the Dream Act, is quiet senators and ask them to approve this legislation," Twitté the US president in the popular social network.
President Barack Obama met today to national mobilization to support the Dream Act, to legalize undocumented students, with a message in his personal account of the social network Twitter.
"If you agree with the approval of the Dream Act, is quiet senators and ask them to approve this legislation," Twitté Obama.
His short message maintains opened a poof link with a broader document that asks the public to contact immediately the senators, because the vote on the legislation is imminent.
"With a vote that they hope soon, now is the time to listen to your voice," he says.
The message was disclosed after Republicans 42 senators have threatened to block the vote of any legislation and if the extension of the tax cuts of the Bush government funding to continue.
Such a blockage, announced in a letter signed by the Republican Senators 42, could affect the vote of the Dream Act and other projects such as the ratification of New START treaty with Russia against the proliferation of nuclear weapons.
When asked about the Republican blocking the Dream Act and other projects, the presidential spokesman Robert Gibbs said he is confidant that once the tax problem is resolved we will be able to set a agende for the rest of the projects.
"I think that we have a lot of time..."
"We all agree that we need to solve this problem tax before the end of the year..."
"I think we can get an agreement at a given moment in this direction and then we can plan the sequence of the rest," he said.
The leader of the Democratic majority in the Senate, Harry Reid, announced Tuesday that it was going to request a "vote of closure of the debate" for the Dream Act, why the initiative to legalize undocumented students could be passed from next Thursday in the Senate, even if the most likely would be the next week.
The Senate version of the Dream Act or Act of Rêve American would legalise 800 thousand young people who arrived in the United States before the age of 16 years, they remained in the country the past five years and they have been accepted by an institution of higher education or by the Army.
But supporters require 60 votes to approve the initiative, why they require support from a large number of Republicans, in moments of partisan organizations project protagonists intense lobbying to ensure the approval of the Act.
The Democrats, the majority which supports the Dream Act, have 58 seats.
However at least one of them, Senator Ben Nelson of Nebraska, said that it would vote against and only a Republican has expressed its support for the law, Richard Lugar of Indiana.
That is why the supporters of the Dream Act require the votes of several Republicans if other Democrats decide to vote against the initiative.
Among the most courted Republicans there Maine senators, Olympia Snowe and Susan Collins, and Senator exleast George Lemieux, of Florida, who has completed the mandate known Senator Mel Martínez.
Other Republicans who have supported in the past the Dream Act are Orrin Hatch, of Utah, and Kay Bailey Hutchinson of Texas, but they have said that they would not support another opportunity.
Another Republican who has supported John McCain, has not defined its position until now.
Even if the House of Representatives has a different version, analysts agree with the fact that the Dream Act are the biggest obstacles in the Senate.
