ROMANO now has the opportunity to be a technician deputy champion and taste the glory offered by the titles for the first time.
The European Union changes the rules for obtaining the visa
People must go to the centres for the Demandeurs Service Visa before their interview in the Consular Section; the lurking waiting time will be reduced.
From 10 January 2011 the processing of visas to the US Embassy and consulates will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will have to present the centres for the Demandeurs Service Visa (CSA, according to its acronyms in English) before their interview in the Consular Section.
The staff of CSA will take biometric information of the applicant, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section before the interview.
The new procedure will present some advantages for candidates, among which include the following:
The total cost to treat the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to get an appointment, another payment for the treatment of visa and another for the mail service book the document.
The aspiring will conduct a single payment which will cover the three services.
The current tariff will remain the same: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, 150 dollars in the case with visa (ci- includes the visas for temporary workers) and US$390 dollars for the visas of traders and investors.
Those wishing to renew their visas will not be present at an interview with the Consular Representative, they will only to the nearest CSA where they will present the documents and taking their fingerprints.
Because of the fact that the biometric information will be taken in the CSA, applicants who wish to a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section stay less time than before.
Similarly, the visa applicants to Consulates in Ciudad Juàrez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the tariff of 26 dollars.
For further information on the new procedure to apply for the visa, visit the following page http://Mexican. Usembassy. gov/boletines/sp101201 Visa FAQs.html
NASA will announce the discovery of extraterrestrial life
The space agency of the United States has cited the press tomorrow to make a discovery that will impact on research of living in space.
The National Aeronautics Administration and Space (NASA) of the United States will report tomorrow, Thursday, a astrobiologique discovery, which could proves the theory of the existence of extraterrestrial life.
The discovery will be presented in a press conference tomorrow, Thursday, at 13:00 pm at the headquarters of NASA in Washington to CAWG experts, the science that explores the origin, evolution, distribution and future of life in the universe.
When she quoted the press, NASA has assured that it would present that will impact on the search for extraterrestrial life ," which has sparked speculation of the experts from other countries.
The discovery could demonstrate the theory that there are similar creatures to us and in ambient hostile-and that was uninhabited and would put on the table the possibility of becoming intelligent beings like humans if their living conditions are improved.
It seems that we are talking about a microbe discovered at the bottom of Mono Lake in the Yosemite National Park, California, who lives in an ambient that was too poisonous for any form of life, because the lake is rich in arsénique.
In any form, the creature uses the arsénique as a way of living and the ability we believe that a similar life could exist on other planets that are not our atmosphere.
According to the astrobiologistes, if these organizations use the arsénique in their metabolism, this proves that "there is another form of life, a second form of life, different from the one we know."
The space agency will communicate the true scope of discoveries in the press conference tomorrow, Thursday.
The conference will participate the géobiologie Pamela Conrad, who is studying the possibility of life on Mars; and the biologist Steven Benner, one of the scientists who are studying Titan (the largest satellite of Saturn), under the prospect of that chemistry is similar to that of the Earth.
