The leader of the Bloc Quebecois, Gilles Duceppe, has also indicated that he could not support the bill, because it is attacking the wrong target.
"We are against, and it seems that all the opposition parties are against, then we shall see what the government will," said Mr. Duceppe.
The immigration NDP critic, Olivia Chow, rejected the criticism of the other side of the hand that his party is not sufficiently strong for illegal immigrants.
"The NDP agree to take action against the smugglers of illegal immigrants and that is what we are doing through another bill, Bill 35," said Mrs Chow.
"We do not support the bill because it takes the Conservatives to refugees and imprisoning the children for at least a year," said Mrs Chow.
The Minister of Immigration, Jason Kenney, has accused the opposition parties to play politics and to ignore the will of Canadians.
"Canadians say massively to Members that they do not tolerate this kind of illegal migration, these criminal operations that target Canada and who treat the country as a doormat."
"They expect that Canada take firm measures," responded the Minister Kenney.
The government has not announced a vote of confidence on his bill, which would have been able to lead the country to elections if its rejection.
A Conservative told the QMI Agency, however, that the government would ask for a vote so that every Member who will then explain to his constituents.
