A global plan to renovate lighting
The UN has proposed yesterday in Cancún a renovation domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries in order to achieve a reduction of greenhouse gas (GHG) which corresponds almost one-third of the additional reduction the need to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is in the wake of the large concrete projects that the UN hopes to adopt in Cancun to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments by industrialized countries.
According to the plan tabled yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs still take 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by lighting Learn or, better, bulbs to light-emitting diodes (LED or "LED" in English), the bulk of 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) GHG issued on the planet to inform humans would be avoided.
The lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
It is the equivalent of 70% of emissions of global car park.
In Copenhagen, the last year, the major emitting countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, are engaged in voluntary reduction plans that are expected to pass the overall GHG emissions of 53 gigatonnes 49 gigatonnes.
From this review, but it will still be 5 gigatonnes to stabilise 2020 climate rising to 2 degrees centigrade in order to avoid it becomes out of control.
In the incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy dissipates as heat and the rest, or 5%, produces light.
With lighting Learn, energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new lamps to LED, reduces the need for energy of two again.
Fluorescent lightbulbs last for an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new lamps to LED, such as those that launched the non-export Philips this week - the company has participated in the study of the UN-the, have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a smouldering bulb, which gives an idea of the economy as possible with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
All new bulbs can also work with rhéostats in addition to emit very little heat.
And they do not contain any mercury.
Several experts have shown reservations against lighting Learn because they contain mercury, and that it must eliminate as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, except if manufacturers implement instructions.
But, says the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the light bulb indicated, but rather the coal-fired power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce electricity wasted in incandescent light bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tonnes of mercury per year.
The report details the gains that would each country through this international program.
For example, Indonesia would save $1 billion a year in electricity purchases and eight million tonnes of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 coal-fired power plants whose construction would be 2.5 billion.
