The unemployment rate remained stable in France in the 3rd quarter
The unemployment rate in France in the sense of the International Labour Office (ILO) remained stable at 9.3% in metropolis (9.7% with the overseas departments), show the data corrected for seasonal variations (CVS) interim published Thursday by the INSEE.
The number of unemployed stood at 2,631 million in city.
The data from the second quarter have been confirmed to 9.3% of the workforce in metropolis and 9.7% with the overseas departments.
A year ago, the unemployment rate is up 0.1 point.
More broadly, 3.4 million people in France were not working in the third quarter but wanted to work, whether or not available in the two weeks to work and that they are looking for a job.
The situation of young people present on the labour market has further deteriorated, with a further increase in the unemployment rate, brought to 24.2% in metropolis (+ 0.9 point in three months, 0.5 point on a year) and 25% by including the overseas departments.
In the third quarter, 637,000 young people aged 15 to 24 were unemployed in the sense of the ILO.
Senior citizens have been a slight increase in unemployment, to 6.4% in metropolis (+ 0.2 points on three months and a year), or US$482 000 people 50 years or more, and 6.6% with the overseas departments.
Only the 25-49 have benefited from the stability of unemployment in the third quarter, to 8.3% in metropolis (-0.1 percentage point in three months, a year) and 8.8% throughout France.
The INSEE no longer releases monthly unemployment rate since 2006, after a controversy over its method of calculation.
Eurostat, the statistical agency of the European Union, continues in contrast and announced Tuesday a rate of 9.8% for France (DOM included) in October after 9.9% in September.
