Clotilde Reiss affair: l'Elysée has exaggerated the mediation of Syria
For more than 10 months, from July 2009 to May 2010, the fate of Clotilde Reiss, the young researcher French arrested in Iran for "spying," was held in breath-testing opinion in France, being alert diplomacy, and accentuated the deterioration of relations between Paris and Tehran.
Under the watchful eye of US diplomats.
The US documents obtained by WikiLeaks and consulted by Le Monde reveal some below this crisis.
They describe how l'Elysée explained his strategy for the Americans, up to their advice for the treatment of their own "hostages" crises in Iran (a small group of hikers).
They show how French officials have sought to convince Washington that the release of the young Frenchwoman had to return the release of Majid Kakavand, an Iranian detained in France and sought by US justice for trafficking of materials to the benefit of the Iranian nuclear programme.
Finally, they place under a bright light the way in which the French Presidency has sought to manipulate the media to give credence to the idea that the Syrian president, Bashar al-Assad, had played a central role in the release of Clotilde Reiss.
In reality, there was nothing.
Diplomatic telegram written in Paris on 12 August 2009 is entitled "Iran: French comments on how to manage cases of hostages."
The advisor to the Elysée Palace for strategic affairs, François Richier, accompanied by the director of the Quai d'Orsay for North Africa and the Middle East, Patrice Paoli, interviewing the American diplomat Kathleen Allegrone.
They explain the French method.
They advise Americans to do the same to repatriate their nationals selected force in Iran.
"Made of noise," they say, ' martelez constantly "in the media the words" fundamental rights of man, "innocence.," "immediate release."
It must in order to embarrass the Iranian regime, sensitive to its image.
"Let all the more that the Iranians ask you to do so."
Because past attempts to discussions by discrete channels, "the silence will solve nothing," the Iranians are "masters in delaying tactics."
Mr. Richier added that the arrest of foreigners is "a familiar Canadian-Iranian tactic: the hostage-taking for political blackmail."
He announced that the release from prison of Clotilde Reiss (which will take place on August 16, when she sought refuge at the Embassy of France) "will require the payment to the Iranians a large sum of money" (230,000 euros bail).
And he said that l'Elysée anticipates other hostage crises, a phenomenon which "will escalate."
The Iranians could "in the near future to stop another some 1,800 citizens French living in Iran," he said.
28 August 2009.
Clotilde Reiss is prison for 12 days, but remains blocked in Iran.
Information is disseminated: the Iranian Majid Kakavand, including the United States are demanding extradition for an illegal trafficking of electronic sensitive material to Iran, is released in Paris, on decision of a judge.
The US Embassy, as many observers questioned this troubling coincidence.
For Washington, which tracks downs Iran's acquisition of material clandestine networks for nuclear program, the enlargement of Majid Khakavand is bad news.
France she accepted a bargain?
The release of the Iranian against that of the French?
In a new interview with Kathleen Allegrone, on 4 September, François Richier ensures that this is not the case.
L'Elysée, he said, has not only been completely taken by surprise by the decision of the judge," but sought to oppose it.
"There has been heated exchanges between the French Presidency and the custody of the seals" (at the time, Michèle Alliot-Marie), but "the government cannot go back on the decision" judicial, says.
Mr. Richier also wants to demonstrate that Majid Kakavand remains under the " monitoring the French intelligence services.
The advisor to the Elysée composed a telephone number, docks, and informed the US diplomat that the Iranian "is currently located in buildings in Paris managed by the Iranian Embassy."
During the detention of Clotilde Reiss in Iran, l'Elysée did not mince his efforts, through releases and "leaks" held in the media, to suggest that the Syrian President Bashar al-Assad plays an "important" and "influential" role of "mediator."
The Americans observe this activity without irony, and find the manipulation is bearing fruit since several press articles depreciation-indeed the official French version.
A telegram dated 25 August 2009 refers to the "blitz' media official French."
On what is based "gratitude" expressed to Assad, wondered the Embassy in Paris.
"Despite their full statements of praise, French officials acknowledge in private that they have only a vague notion of what the Syrians have actually done."
The document then examines the reasons that led l'Elysée to pay in this fiction.
The intense effort of communication "seeks to validate Sarkozy's policy of opening to Syria," analysis says.
A policy launched in 2008, which "was seen by many critics in France and abroad, as premature and undeservedly criminalised."
"Exaggerating the Syrian role," Paris seeks to demonstrate to Syria what praise it can draw in playing a constructive role in the region. "
The aim is also to "sow the seeds of discord between Syria and Iran."
The US Embassy knows good source.
On 11 August, François Richier gave him: "Of course, we do not know whether the Syrians have done anything."
"But we have thanked even."
"This should at least confusion among the Iranians."
Clotilde Reiss returned to France on 16 May 2010.
Nicolas Sarkozy received at the Élysée Palace.
In a news release, he thanked the Presidents of Brazil, Senegal, and Syria, for their "active role in favour of the liberation of our compatriot."
No online games for the young Koreans past midnight
The South Korean government will adopt a "Cinderella" law which will ban adolescents to play online games after midnight by blocking their access, reported government officials.
A bill will be submitted to Parliament in December to ask the online game companies to block access to these games after midnight, youth aged less than 16 years, have said representatives of the ministries of culture and family.
"Many children play in these games all night and then difficult to study and to have a normal life at the school during the day."
"We believe that this law is necessary to ensure their health and their right to sleep," said BSFO Jo Rin, the departmental in charge of the bill.
Online gambling will again be available to 6 hours of the morning.
Companies will have a year to prepare for the application of the law is clarified.
The government also plans to ask companies to limit the time for daily access to these games for young people whose parents so request, added the responsible.
It will also provide people who are calling for free software that allow us to limit the time spent on the Internet.
South Korea is one of the most "connected" countries and the newspapers regularly about various facts related to an intensive use of the Internet.
The country is also the undisputed champion of global online competitions.
In November, South Korea had won four gold medals at the World Cyber Games, facing 58 other nations.
