The last meeting of the Governing Council of the European Central Bank (ECB) for the year should be the opportunity to clarify the exit procedures, or at least, to announce the arrest of many unconventional operations of monetary policy which must be achèver at the end of the year.
Crisis in European sovereign debt requires, the Frankfurt d'Émission institute can not afford to be as compelling subject to aggravate a tense situation today on the bond markets.
The political cost would be even higher.
Yesterday, on the occasion of a press conference, the French Finance Minister Christine Lagarde, and welcomed the active role played by the ECB in favour of the resolution of the crisis of the debts of the states in Europe.
It did not say whether it believed that the central bank should do more, increasing its sovereign bond purchasing program.
"I reserve my thinking to my European partners (...) ."
The day before, in Brussels, during his hearing by the Committee on Economic and Monetary Affairs of the European Parliament, the ECB's president, Jean-Claude Trichet, has not shown more disert about his intentions, merely to indicate that the program to purchase of state securities on the secondary market "continues" and that "we will see what we decide" at the meeting this Thursday.
Only certainty: the ECB will keep its main interest rate unchanged at 1%, its lowest level since May 2009.
In fact, purchases of Treasury bonds by the ECB have doubled the last week, to nearly US$1.35 billion euros.
And, according to the indiscretions of market operators, it would have made new purchases of Portuguese and Irish debt, yesterday.
In total, the central banks of the Eurosystem have purchased for 67 billion euros since May 2010.
Among market operators, expectations of further purchases are no doubt (see page 29).
Economists do not expect a significant change of course.
If the lending operations to more than three months have already disappeared from the arsenal of the ECB, the latter still conducts unlimited allocations of cash under generous conditions and to varying 1931-1976 a week to three months.
Economists now expect that this device is extended for a few months.
"I cannot imagine that it amends significantly its program."
"Otherwise this would take the risk of provoking new tensions in short term," says Michael Schubert, economist of Commerzbank.
"A gradual exit announced during the first quarter 2011 seems more likely," " anticipates Norbert Bräms, an economist for Sal.
Oppenheim.
In terms of its interventions in the market of the public debt, "the ECB should maintain a volume of purchase of these obligations to facilitate a sluggish market," Norbert Bräms.
Given the importance of European banks' exposures to sovereign debt markets in the euro area, the d'Émission Institute has no other choice than to maintain its presence on the market.
"He must at all costs to replace the lack of investors on the market and act so as to prevent a runaway yields paid by the most fragile states," reflected an important bond manager yesterday.
Because if interest rates are soaring, the states will be even more embarrassed to reduce debt, otherwise the stabilize.
The preservation of the euro is at this price.
