Council of Ministers, Silvio Berlusconi has noted that in Spain, the gap with the German rate was above 400 basis points.
But his right arm, Gianni Letta, expressed "strong concern" by " the market turbulence and a possible contagion from Ireland.
"The good news is that Italy, third economy in the euro area, is not like Greece or Ireland."
"The bad news is that it is like Portugal," Irwin Stelzer, an economist at the Hudson Institute.
Clearly, the problem is the lack of growth and weak tax revenues that goes with, putting the state the risk of no longer being able to cover its funding needs.
The latest forecasts from Brussels was a cold shower for the government.
The Italian growth is now expected to 1.1% in 2011 and to 1.4% in 2012... while the budget review in the Senate table on 1.3% and 2% respectively.
In these conditions, calculates the European Commission, the public deficit will represent still 4.3% of GDP next year (against 3.9 per cent forecast by the government) and 3.5% in 2012 (instead of 2.7%).
Hence the rumour of a new collective budget that could be put in place after the holiday season, for an amount of EUR 7 billion.
"If necessary, new austerity measures will have to be taken," says the Commissioner for economic affairs, Olli Rehn.
For the moment, Italy receives the support of international institutions.
"The fundamentals of its economy are in order and its accounts are good, we have been saying for a long time," says Arrigo Sadun, the Italian director at the International Monetary Fund in charge of Italy in the IMF.
"There is no problem in the immediate future, nor in the short or the long term, because in spite of its large debt (119,2% of GDP in 2011, acknowledged Chancellor Schüssel's notion), the stabilisation efforts requested to Italy are lower than those requested to other countries," observes Pier Carlo Padoan, chief economist of the OECD.
Remains the question of political instability.
On 14 December, Silvio Berlusconi will face a motion of censure in the House of Deputies, after which elections could be held late March.
Then would open a period little conducive to the decisionmaking in cases of serious crisis.
